[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(12) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Took the bones of Saul.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Moved by the story of Rizpah’s tender care, and wishing to show that he cherished no enmity against the house of Saul, David buried honourably the remains of Saul and of his descendants. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1Samuel 31:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " it is said that the Philistines fastened the body of Saul “to the wall of Beth-shan;” here, that the men of Jabesh-gilead took them secretly from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the street. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The two statements are quite consistent, for the exact place where the Philistines hung up to public view the body of the slain and defeated monarch was the broad space or square, just inside the gate, where the people were wont to gather; and it was from the same place that they were taken. Most MSS. of the LXX. add to the previous verse: “And they were taken down, and Dan the son of Joa, of the descendants of the giant, took them down.”",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "2 Samuel 21:12",
